            "formula": "\nSWITCH(\n{fldADNGkh6hYRu2py},\n1, \"Deficient: Group thinking is deficient, as self-orientation is extremely high, prioritizing one's own interest to a great extent at the expense of trust and collective success.\",\n2, \"Very Low: Group thinking is very low as self-orientation is very high, with a clear preference for self-interest, negatively impacting trust.\",\n3, \"Low: Group thinking is low as self-orientation is high, with a significant tendency to prioritize self-interest over collective success and trust.\",\n4, \"Below Average: Group thinking is below average as self-orientation is moderately high, with key areas requiring improvement to reduce the priority of self-interest.\",\n5, \"Average: Group thinking is average as self-orientation is acceptable, with room for improvement but with a reasonable balance between self-interest and building trust.\",\n6, \"Satisfactory: Group thinking is satisfactory as self-orientation is moderate, with solid aspects and some areas to refine in reducing the priority of self-interest.\",\n7, \"Moderately High: Group thinking is moderately high as self-orientation is low, with a notable focus on building trust and collective success rather than self-interest.\",\n8, \"High: Group thinking is high as self-orientation is minimal, almost nonexistent, overwhelmingly prioritizing building trust and collective success over self-interest.\",\n9, \"Very High: Group thinking is very high as self-orientation is very low, strongly prioritizing building trust and collective success, with minimal focus on self-interest.\",\n10, \"Outstanding: Group thinking is outstanding as self-orientation is null, completely absent, focused exclusively on building trust and collective success without considering self-interest.\",\n\"The score is out of range or not a number\"\n)",
            "referencedFieldIds": [
