        {
          "type": "formula",
          "options": {
            "isValid": true,
            "formula": "SWITCH(\n  {fldfzM5bAJp3vQuVc},\n  1, \"Deficient: Group thinking is deemed deficient, as self-orientation is outstanding. The swift completion of tasks does not translate into quality work, with an exclusive focus on meeting deadlines without considering quality.\",\n  2, \"Very Low: Group thinking is very low, as individuals prioritize their own interests, with minimal connection between task delivery speed and work quality, indicating minimal concern for the final outcome.\",\n  3, \"Low: Group thinking is low, given high self-orientation, overwhelmingly prioritizing task delivery speed over work quality.\",\n  4, \"Below Average: Group thinking falls below average, as self-orientation is moderately high, with a notable emphasis on delivery speed at the expense of work quality.\",\n  5, \"Average: Group thinking is average, as individuals exhibit a self-orientation with an acceptable balance between task delivery speed and work quality.\",\n  6, \"Satisfactory: Group thinking is satisfactory, as the self-orientation of individuals is moderate, with room for improvement but a reasonable balance between speed and quality.\",\n  7, \"Moderately High: Group thinking is moderately high, as self-orientation is low, with a notable emphasis on delivery speed while maintaining a solid standard of quality.\",\n  8, \"High: Group thinking is high, as self-orientation is minimal, almost nonexistent, demonstrating that task delivery speed and work quality are complementary.\",\n  9, \"Very High: Group thinking is very high, as self-orientation is very low, with a clear understanding that quality is as crucial as speed in task delivery.\",\n  10, \"Outstanding: Group thinking is outstanding, as self-orientation is deficient, perfectly balancing speed and quality, showcasing an exceptional commitment to both aspects.\",\n  \"The score is out of range or not a number\"\n)",
